    <!-- FAQs -->
    <section id="faqs" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I get Vietnamese citizenship through investment?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            No. Vietnam does not have a citizenship-by-investment program and does not allow dual citizenship. Long-term
            investors can apply for Permanent Residence Cards after extended lawful residence (typically 5+ years with
            proven contributions), but this doesn't lead to citizenship. Most foreign investors maintain their original
            citizenship while holding renewable investor visas.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the minimum investment amount?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            There's no fixed minimum for most sectors. Charter capital must be "sufficient for stated business activities"—
            authorities assess this case-by-case. Service companies typically need $10,000-$50,000; manufacturing $100,000+.
            For capital contribution to existing companies (without establishing new entity), minimum is typically VND 3
            billion (~$120,000 USD) for investor visa eligibility.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I own property in Vietnam?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            Yes, with limitations. Foreigners can own apartments (maximum 30% of units in any building) and houses in
            designated areas, with 50-year renewable leases (not freehold). Land cannot be owned—only leased. Property
            ownership alone doesn't qualify for investor visa; you need an active business investment.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long can I stay on an investor visa?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            Investor visas (ĐT category) are issued for 1-5 years, matching your Investment Registration Certificate
            duration. Multiple-entry visas allow unlimited entry/exit. After arrival, register for a Temporary Residence
            Card (TRC) for more convenience. Visas are renewable as long as your investment remains active.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I bring my family?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            Yes. Spouses and children can apply for dependent visas (TT category) based on your investor status. Each
            family member needs their own visa application. Spouses can work if they obtain their own work permit.
            Children can attend international schools (fees: $10,000-$25,000/year at top schools).
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What are the tax implications?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            Corporate Income Tax is 20% (lower rates for certain industries). Personal Income Tax for residents is
            progressive (5-35%) on worldwide income. Residents are those present 183+ days/year OR having a permanent
            residence. Vietnam has Double Taxation Agreements with many countries. Consult a tax professional familiar
            with both Vietnamese and your home country tax law.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Final Verdict -->
    <section id="verdict" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

      <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
        <p class="text-primary-900 mb-4">
          Vietnam's investor visa is ideal for entrepreneurs who want active business involvement in one of Asia's
          fastest-growing economies. The lack of citizenship pathway and dual citizenship prohibition means this is
          purely a business and lifestyle play—not a second passport program. But for those focused on building a
          company, Vietnam offers exceptional value: low operating costs, educated workforce, and strategic position
          in ASEAN supply chains.
        </p>
        <p class="text-primary-900 mb-4">
          Healthcare is the main consideration for long-term investors. While international hospitals in HCMC and
          Hanoi provide good care, complex procedures often require evacuation to Singapore or Bangkok. International
          health insurance with evacuation coverage is non-negotiable—the public healthcare system isn't designed for
          expat needs.
        </p>
        <p class="text-primary-900">
          The investment threshold is flexible (no fixed minimum for most sectors), making Vietnam accessible compared
          to programs requiring $500,000+. However, expect complexity: sector restrictions, local partner requirements
          for some industries, and ongoing compliance obligations require professional support. Budget $5,000-$15,000
          for setup costs and plan for a 2-4 month timeline.
        </p>
      </div>

